# Architecture & code rules

## Master description (Flutter stack)

This workspace rule is the **single master description** of the DaysTracker **Flutter stack** for code under **`lib/`**: Clean Architecture layering, BLoC/Cubit, DI (`get_it` / `injectable`), domain and data models, repositories, navigation, presentation (UI/theming), and testing expectations. Portable or shared skills (e.g. **Flutter mobile patterns** outside this repo) should **mirror** this rule, not redefine the stack in parallel. If any other text disagrees with this file on structure or stack choices, follow **Conflict resolution (DaysTracker)** — for `lib/**`, **this rule wins** over duplicated skill or prompt content.

---

App code for this package lives under **`lib/`** only. Layering, orchestration, and dependency rules apply to all Dart files matched by `globs`. **Presentation** and **testing** guidance below applies to the same code; it does not relax any forbidden imports or layer boundaries. If other sources disagree, follow **Conflict resolution (DaysTracker)** (workspace rule `daystracker-conflict-resolution`).

## Layering (Clean Architecture)

- Organize code as **domain → data → presentation**. Dependencies point **inward**: presentation depends on domain abstractions; data implements them.
- **Forbidden**: `presentation` importing concrete **data** types (repository implementations, DAOs, API clients, DTO mappers tied to IO).
- **Forbidden**: calling **DAOs / local DB / raw API clients** directly from widgets or BLoCs. All persistence and network I/O go through **repository implementations** behind **domain interfaces**.
- **Forbidden**: `domain` or `data` importing **routing**, **widgets**, or **Flutter** except where a thin boundary is explicitly allowed (e.g. data layer may use `dart:io` / plugins only inside adapters).
- **Domain** defines: repository **interfaces**, a small set of **Failure** types, pure **entities/models**, **enums**, and optional **pure functions** for rules (e.g. day counting) with no I/O.
- **Data** implements repositories, owns Drift/DAO/API/DTOs, maps to domain entities, and maps low-level errors to domain **Failure**s.
- **Presentation** contains: UI widgets, **BLoCs/Cubits**, routing glue, and presentation-only helpers.

## Orchestration

- **BLoCs/Cubits** call **repository interfaces** (and pure domain helpers where needed). There is **no** dedicated use-case class layer.
- **Avoid** duplicating the same sequence of repository calls across multiple BLoCs or widgets. If a workflow is non-trivial, add a **single** higher-level method on the **repository interface** (implemented in data) so orchestration stays in one place.
- BLoCs focus on **UI state**, **events**, and mapping **Failure** → user-visible error states; keep business rules that do not need I/O in **domain** (pure functions / entities).

## Domain models

- Domain entities are **plain Dart classes**: immutable fields, `copyWith`, **`Equatable`** for value equality.
- **Do not** use **`freezed`** for domain entities or DTOs.
- Domain models must not import **Flutter**, **widgets**, or **platform/UI** packages.

## State management

- Use **`flutter_bloc`** (BLoC or Cubit).
- BLoCs/Cubits depend only on **domain abstractions** (repository interfaces), injected via **`get_it`** + **`injectable`**.
- Use **events + handlers** for non-trivial flows; apply **`bloc_concurrency`** transformers where overlapping events matter (e.g. `restartable`, `droppable`) when the dependency is added.

## Repositories

- Declare **abstract** repository interfaces in **domain**.
- Implement them in **data** as `*RepositoryImpl` with **`@Injectable(as: RepositoryInterface)`** (or project-equivalent `injectable` pattern).
- Repository methods that can fail return **`Either<Failure, T>`** from **`dartz`**. BLoCs/widgets depend only on the **interface**, never the implementation.

## Errors and `dartz`

- Use **`dartz`**: repository (and similar domain-facing) APIs return **`Either<Failure, T>`** or **`Either<Failure, Unit>`** for operations that can fail.
- Define a small, consistent set of **`Failure`** types (e.g. sealed hierarchy) in **domain**. Do not throw raw exceptions across the domain boundary into BLoCs; **map** exceptions to **`Failure`** inside **data** (typically in repository implementations).
- BLoCs **`fold`** on **`Either`** (or equivalent) and emit error states with **localized** messages where appropriate.

## Dates and time

- Store and pass **UTC** `DateTime` in **domain** and **data**.
- Convert to local time only at the **presentation** boundary (formatting, pickers, calendar UI).
- Prefer explicit naming when both matter (e.g. `startUtc`); never mix UTC and local in one field without naming it clearly.

## Persistence and offline behavior

- Long-term state uses **local DB** (e.g. Drift/SQLite) **behind** repositories, not from BLoCs.
- Background location, visits, and aggregates are loaded/saved only through **repositories**.
- **DTOs** and API types stay in **data**; do not leak them into **domain** or **presentation**.

## Models, unions, and serialization

- Use **`freezed`** only for: BLoC **events**, BLoC **states**, and sealed unions that are **strictly** presentation/state concerns.
- DTOs: **`json_serializable`** (or project standard); keep in **data** and map to plain domain entities.
- Do not expose DTOs or raw HTTP types outside **data**.

## Navigation

- Use **`auto_route`** consistently; define routes in one place.
- Avoid ad-hoc **`Navigator.push`** from random widgets; use the generated router / `context.router`.
- **Domain** and **data** must not depend on routing code.

## Platform, location, and privacy

- **`geolocator`**, **`permission_handler`**, platform channels, and similar **IO** live in **data** (or a **`core`** adapter consumed only by **data**), not in BLoCs/widgets directly.
- No analytics or cloud sync types in **domain** unless the product explicitly adds them; **privacy-first / local-first** is the default assumption.

## Internationalization

- User-visible strings go through **generated l10n** (e.g. `context.l10n` / ARB). No hardcoded user-facing English in widgets (debug strings are OK).

## Dependency injection (`injectable` / `get_it`)

- Register repository implementations with **`@Injectable(as: Interface)`**; register BLoCs/Cubits with **`@injectable`** per project conventions.
- After changing **`@injectable`**, **`@freezed`**, **`@JsonSerializable`**, or **`@RoutePage`**, run the project’s **codegen** (e.g. `dart run build_runner build --delete-conflicting-outputs` or your **`Makefile`** / **`docs/COMMANDS.md`** target).
- **Never** hand-edit generated files; fix the source annotations instead.

## Day-counting semantics (DaysTracker)

- **Inclusive** calendar-day semantics, **timezone**, and **Schengen / 183-day** interpretation must live in **documented domain logic** (single module or pure functions), not scattered in BLoCs. When in doubt, follow the product spec; do not invent rules in the UI layer.

## Presentation: UI composition

- Prefer **composition over inheritance**: small widgets and helpers composed into screens instead of deep widget subclasses.
- **One screen, one primary job**: keep `build` methods readable; extract private widgets or files when a tree gets hard to scan.
- **Explicit UI states** for important surfaces: loading, success, empty, and error—avoid ambiguous half-loaded layouts (how you *show* state is here; how BLoCs emit failure/loading follows **State management** and **Errors and `dartz`** above).

## Presentation: Theming and design system

- **Single `ThemeData` / extensions**: colors, typography, spacing, and radii live in one place; screens use tokens (theme, `ThemeExtension`, or shared constants), not one-off literals except for true one-offs.
- **Accessibility**: respect text scaling and contrast; do not rely on color alone for meaning (pair with icons or labels where thresholds matter).
- Align new UI with **design docs** (`docs/design/*`) and Penpot when those exist.

## Testing strategy

- **Goal**: unit tests for pure/domain logic; **BLoC/Cubit tests** for non-trivial state transitions; **widget tests** for critical user flows.
- **Early product stage**: skipping tests on the first iteration of a feature is acceptable per **Process Rules**; once behavior stabilizes, add tests or a follow-up task.
- **Boundaries**: mock/fake at **repository interfaces** (or thin fakes), not inside low-level data adapters, unless testing that layer directly.
- Keep tests **small and focused**; prefer Arrange–Act–Assert and readable names over coverage theater.
